, Devon, England":"Wyke, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wrey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Wray Barton (Devon).","2  English: nickname, perhaps ‘the twisted, crooked one’, from Middle English  <i>wry(e)</i> ‘awry’, a derivative of Old English  <i>wrīgian</i> ‘to turn’. It is possible, however, that  <i>le Wrey</i> (1313) is a scribal error for  <i>de Wrey</i>, and that the following early bearers belong under (1).","3  N English:  see  Wray  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wray","meanings":["English (northern):","from Middle English <i>wra</i> (Old Norse <i>vrá</i>) ‘nook, corner of land’, a topographic name for someone who lived at or by a nook, corner of land, or isolated place, or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Wray in Tunstall (Lancashire), Wrea in Kirkham (Lancashire), and High and Low Wreah in Hensingham (Cumberland). The name was taken to Ulster by a Yorkshire family in the reign of Elizabeth I, and was used interchangeably in the counties of Derry and Donegal with <i>Raw</i>, <i>Ray</i>, <i>Rea</i>, and occasionally   McRae  .","common post-medieval spelling of   Ray  ,   Rae  , or   Ree  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Wrey was born in 1132, in Wyke, Devon, England. He married Sybil Abbott about 1154, in Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 6 sons. He died in 1195, in his hometown, at the age of 63."},"et":{"1132–1195":"1132–1195","1134–Female":"1134–Surnud","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1157–Male":"1157–Surnud","1161–Male":"1161–Surnud","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1167–Male":"1167–Surnud","1170–1248":"1170–1248","about 1161":"umbes 1161","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1195":"1195","1161":"1161","1170":"1170","L. 1138":"1138","1248":"1248","1157":"1157","1167":"1167","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","about 1167":"umbes 1167","about 1157":"umbes 1157","about 1154":"umbes 1154","about 1155":"umbes 1155","about 1164":"umbes 1164","Wyke, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Wyke, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Wyke, South Tawton, Devon, England":"South Tawton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wyke, Devon, England":"Wyke, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"fi":{"1132–1195":"1132–1195","1134–Female":"1134–Kuollut","1155–Male":"1155–Kuollut","1157–Male":"1157–Kuollut","1161–Male":"1161–Kuollut","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1167–Male":"1167–Kuollut","1170–1248":"1170–1248","about 1161":"noin 1161","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1195":"1195","1161":"1161","1170":"1170","L. 1138":"1138","1248":"1248","1157":"1157","1167":"1167","1134":"1134","1155":"1155","about 1167":"noin 1167","about 1157":"noin 1157","about 1154":"noin 1154","about 1155":"noin 1155","about 1164":"